Annotations of JPA:

Full working annotations of JPA:-
Ex:

import javax.persistence.*;

@Entity
@Table(name = "users")
public class User {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;

    @Column(name = "user_name", nullable = false, length = 100)
    private String name;

    @Embedded
    private Address address;

    @Enumerated(EnumType.STRING)
    private Status status;

    // getters and setters
}

@Embeddable
class Address {
    private String street;
    private String city;
    // getters and setters
}

enum Status {
    ACTIVE, INACTIVE, BANNED
}

Interview Tips:

@Entity: Marks a class as a JPA entity (table).
@Table: Customizes the table name.
@Id: Primary key.
@GeneratedValue: How the primary key is generated.
@Column: Customizes column mapping.
@Embeddable/@Embedded: For reusable, grouped fields.
@Enumerated: For storing enums (prefer EnumType.STRING).

Best practices:
Always use @Id and @GeneratedValue for primary keys.
Use @Column for custom column names or constraints.
Use @Embeddable for value objects (like Address).
Use @Enumerated(EnumType.STRING) for enums.


Using Embedded Classes with @Embeddable and @Embedded

What it does: Allows you to group related fields into a separate class and embed them in
your entity. The fields of the embedded class become columns in the entity’s table.
Usage:
Mark the class to be embedded with @Embeddable.
Use @Embedded in the entity.
Example:

import javax.persistence.Embeddable;

@Embeddable
public class Address {
    private String street;
    private String city;
    // getters, setters
}

import javax.persistence.Embedded;

@Entity
public class User {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;

    @Embedded
    private Address address;
    // other fields, getters, setters
}
The User table will have columns for address_street and address_city.

4. Storing Enumerations with @Enumerated

What it does: Specifies how Java enums are stored in the database (as strings or ordinals).
Usage: Place it above the enum field.

import javax.persistence.Enumerated;
import javax.persistence.EnumType;

public enum Status {
    ACTIVE, INACTIVE, BANNED
}

@Entity
public class User {
    @Enumerated(EnumType.STRING)
    private Status status;
}

EnumType.STRING: Stores the enum as a string (e.g., "ACTIVE").
EnumType.ORDINAL: Stores the enum as an integer (e.g., 0, 1, 2).
Best practice: Use STRING for readability and safety.
